VIRAL HEMORRHAGIC SEPTICEMIA, FISH - USA (02): (OHIO)
*****************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Fri 4 Jul 2008
Source: Cleveland.com, The Plain Dealer report [edited]
<http://www.cleveland.com/outdoors/index.ssf/2008/07/fish_virus_concerns_called_unf.html>


Fish virus concerns called unfounded
------------------------------------
A fish virus discovered at Clear Fork Reservoir
near Mansfield, Ohio, has some worried about
viral hemorrhagic septicemia (VHS) contaminating
Ohio's fish hatcheries, rivers, and reservoirs
and the virus racing to the Mississippi River.

It is the 1st time VHS has been detected outside
of the Great Lakes, but the worries are
unfounded, said Ohio hatchery coordinator Elmer
Heyob of the Ohio Division of Wildlife.

Wildlife crews took eggs from at least 2 infected
muskies at Clear Fork last spring [2008] for its
London Hatchery, not knowing the fish would test
positive weeks later for VHS. Rainbow trout being
raised at London have since been shipped to
Ohio's premier steelhead trout facility, the Castalia State Fish Hatchery.

Because of VHS and other viruses, precautions are
routinely taken to prevent the spread of VHS
around Ohio, especially between hatcheries, Heyob
said. Salmonid eggs -- including rainbow and
steelhead trout -- are treated with 50
parts-per-million of an iodine solution that is
absorbed by the fish eggs to kill any virus. The
young muskies hatched from the Clear Fork
Reservoir eggs have been healthy, and will be
tested again before their release into Ohio reservoirs.

The virus has devastated fish hatcheries in
Europe, but the VHS strain found in the Great
Lakes is far less virulent, said Heyob.

[Byline: D'Arcy Egan]

